description: From Dutch boomken (“shrub, little tree”), equivalent to boom +‎ -kin. Note that the English word boom is etymologically related to the aforementioned in the sense of "large stem", or "big tree". Compare German Baumke, Bäumchen.

entries.meaning: A clumsy, unsophisticated person; a yokel.
(nautical) A short boom or spar used to extend a sail or secure a stay.
Dance, a series of reels, Scottish.
examples: They mix with Dancers, who now advance to the front, where a bumpkin, or dance of many interwoven reels, is performed; after which the Bride is led to a seat, and some of her Maidens sit by her.
